{{Blurimage|file=Japan1.jpg|caption=A common room within '''Level 51'''.}}{{Blurimage|file=Japan2.webp|caption=An enclosed room.}}{{Blurimage|file=Japan3.webp|caption=A large, well-lit central room.}}
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀<font size=2.5>Being among the most pervasive and mysterious levels of the Backrooms — in no small part due to its persistent anomalous properties — '''The Illimitable Temple''' (Level 51) resembles an ancient religious temple, presumably of Japanese origin. Ancient kanji symbols can be found scattered around the level's many corridors in arbitrary patterns. The entire locale is constructed out of wood and paper — materials typically used in the construction of Japanese homes, among other things. Kanji symbols present on the walls are significantly modified from their counterparts in [[The Frontrooms]], often completely losing their original meaning as a result. Despite clearly being modeled after a Japanese temple, the locale is devoid of any texts or objects that would indicate the structure's historical and religious significance, such as religious texts and statues. Liquids within the level coalesce into puddles; as a vast majority of surfaces are hydrophobic. Scattered torches and lamp posts can be found throughout many rooms, with the fire-esque substance contained within them behaving much like [[Object 5|Greek Fire]].

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀An abundant supply of [[Object 1|Almond Water]] can be found in containers typically used for storing sake<ref>A Japanese alcohol with a high alcoholic content.</ref>, seldom containing other substances such as [[Object 12|Liquid Pain]] and the like. Almond Water may also be found coalescing on windows located in large rooms. Such windows show a variety of grass-covered hillsides and mountains — resemblant of rural Japan. The outside areas of '''Level 51''' are confined spatial anomalies, essentially functioning as thresholds into other levels, most prominently [[Level 909]]. The windows are covered in a light mist on the interior side as a result of humidity and the occasional light drizzles from outside.

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀Whilst the structure of '''Level 51''' suggests the existence of multiple floors, access to said floors is infeasible — a vast majority, if not all of the stairwells within the level are completely inaccessible, and other attempts to reach higher floors are inconclusive. The entire level has an active convection cycle which persists throughout the entire level; this cycle of warm and cool air seems to defy the laws of physics altogether, as it is able to pass through structures and access a vast majority of rooms, which are typically closed off completely by the abundant shoji<ref>Japanese sliding doors; typically located within a vast majority of places across Japan.</ref> doors within the level. The climate of the locale is typically warm, measuring around 71°F (21.7°C) on average, albeit with significant deviations as much as ten degrees in certain areas. </font>


----
<span style="font-family:Montserrat"><center><big><big><big>MENTAL HAZARDS 精神的な危険</big></big></big></center></span>
----
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀<font size=2.5>'''Level 51''' contains a wide variety of mental hazards which exhibit detrimental effects on wanderers. Many of those who have visited the level have reported a distinct and all-encompassing form of dementia in which memories are graudally erased, being replaced with profound and grotesque visions of Japanese history. Whilst these visions tend to vary between wanderer accounts, they are most commonly pertaining to Japan during the Second World War — including their atrocities against the Chinese population during the Second Sino-Japanese War, often in extreme grotesque detail.

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀Whilst these visions and memories may seem harmless in the short term, studies have shown that they are extremely detrimental on one's mental state; with many wanderers who have visited the level either '''committing suicide''' or succumbing to [[Phenomenon 35|Roth Syndrome]] after an extended period of time. Whilst the effects tend to gradually get worse the more time an individual spends within the level, even short visits have been proven to cause irreparable permanent psychological effects to them. 

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀Although most methods to reverse the effects certainly ''have'' been tried, such as consumption of Almond Water or electroshock therapy to name a few, it often results in the symptoms merely getting worse. Those of whom did not already kill themselves or succumb to the Wretched Cycle tend to exhibit violent and uncontrollable tendencies, often developing mental illnesses such as schizophrenia and post-traumatic stress disorder. Individuals often feel an intense patriotism for Japan, often seeking out other individuals and incapacitating them in cruel and unusual ways.<ref>Debatably the most infamous example of this is Elias Nieminen, a Finnish individual who exited the level, only to kill almost every individual within a classified M.E.G. contingent.</ref> Notable cases of such individuals are listed below:

<div class="lightblock"><span class="titlebox">CASE I. John Merkel</span>
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀'''Status: <span style="color: green">ALIVE; IN CUSTODY</span>'''<br>
Reported with having violent tendencies. When captured and interrogated, he repeatedly mumbled the phrase "''we're losing''" both in English and Japanese, along with attempting to kill the interrogator.
</div>

<div class="lightblock"><span class="titlebox">CASE II. Daniel Mitt</span>
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀'''Status: <span style="color: red">DECEASED</span>'''<br>
Captured by the [[Republic of Aurielle]] after killing 3 members in a now defunct exploratory settlement. Was promptly executed after an unsuccessful interrogation.
</div>

<div class="lightblock"><span class="titlebox">CASE II. Albert Reeves</span>
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀'''Status: <span style="color: green">ALIVE; WHEREABOUTS UNKNOWN</span>'''<br>
Among the worst examples of a victim of '''Level 51''', who had visited the level during [[Phenomenon 12|The Flicker]] only to violently murder around ten individuals within New London — shortly before the base became defunct and was abandoned. Suspect is currently missing.
</div>

<div class="lightblock"><span class="titlebox">CASE IV. Elias Nieminen</span>
